{{About|the nationalist greeting used in India|the Indian newspaper of the same name|Jai Hind (newspaper)}} '''Jai Hind''' ({{Lang-hi|जय हिन्द}}) ({{Lang-bn|জয় হিন্দ}}) is a salutation, slogan, and [[battle cry]] most commonly used in [[India]] to indicate [[patriotism]] towards India (also known as [[Etymology of India|Hind]]). It translates roughly to "Victory to India"<ref>{{cite book |title= A comprehensive history of modern India |last= Chopra |first= Pram Nath |year= 2003 |publisher= [[Sterling Publishing]] |isbn= 81-207-2506-9 |page= 283 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=RAON5AW4yUEC&pg=PA283&dq=jai+hind+victory+to+india&client=firefox-a&cd=4#v=onepage&q=jai%20hind%20victory%20to%20india&f=false |accessdate= 17 February 2010}}</ref> or "Long live India".<ref>{{cite book |title= The Rise and Fall of the British Empire |last= James |first= Lawrence |year= 1997 |publisher= Macmillan |isbn= 978-0-312-16985-5<!-- 8120725069--> |page= 548 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=4DMS3r_BxOYC&pg=RA4-PA548-IA8&dq=jai+hind+long+live+india&client=firefox-a&cd=7#v=onepage&q=jai%20hind%20long%20live%20india&f=false |accessdate= 17 February 2010}}</ref> The term was coined and was used by [[Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose]]<ref name=amzn-brothers>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Brothers-Against-Raj-Leonard-Gordon/dp/0231074433|title=Brothers Against the Raj|author=Leonard A. Gordon|year=1990|publisher=Columbia University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A tale of two cities|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/a-tale-of-two-cities/article5635343.ece|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref> of the [[Indian National Army]] as a shortened version of ''Jai Hindustan Ki''. <gallery widths="200px" heights="200px"> Katni1.jpg|An old building in [[Katni]] built in commemoration of India's freedom, with statues of [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[Mohandas K. Gandhi]] and [[Subhas Chandra Bose]], with "Jai Hind" written in Roman letters and [[Devanagari]] script. JAI HIND.jpg|The book "Jai Hind" authored by Ramchandra Moreshwar Karkare. 1947 India Flag 3½ annas.jpg|Independent India's first postage stamp. Jai Hind Post-mark.gif|Indian commemorative post-mark of "[[Jai Hind postmark|Jai Hind]]". </gallery>
==In popular culture== A follower of Indian nationalist [[Subhas Chandra Bose]], Ramchandra Moreshwar Karkare, of [[Gwalior|Gwalher]] (Gwalior) Madhya Bharat, wrote a patriotic drama ''Jai Hind'' in March 1947 and published a book in [[Hindi]], with the same title. Later, Karkare became Congress president of Central India Province.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}
The [[Jai Hind postmark]] was the first commemorative [[postmark]] of Independent India, and was issued on the day of independence, 15 August 1947.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} "जय हिन्द" is also stated on the first, [[List_of_postage_stamps_of_India#1947|Independence series of Indian stamps]].
The phrase is used on [[All India Radio]] at the end of a broadcast.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} It occurs in the patriotic song "[[Aye Mere Watan Ke Logo]]" sung by [[Lata Mangeshkar]] in 1963.<ref>{{cite book|last=Chaturvedi|first=Mamta |title=Filmi & non-filmi songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=459ay5Ai2l4C&pg=PA38&dq=Jay+Hind&cd=1#v=onepage&q=Jay%20Hind&f=false|year=2004|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books|isbn=81-288-0299-2|page=38}}</ref>
[[Mahatma Gandhi]] sent a piece of crocheted, cotton lace made from yarn personally spun by himself, with the central motif ''Jai Hind'', to British Royal couple [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] as a wedding gift in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/HMTheQueen/TheQueenandspecialanniversaries/DiamondAnniversary/60facts.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 10, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008194238/http://www.royal.gov.uk/HMTheQueen/TheQueenandspecialanniversaries/DiamondAnniversary/60facts.aspx |archivedate=October 8, 2015 }}</ref>
The phrase has also given its name to * ''Jai Hind'' (1999), a Hindi film, made by actor-director [[Manoj Kumar]]<ref>{{IMDb title|0286728|Jai Hind}}</ref> * The comedy show ''[[Jay Hind!]]'' (2009) * [[Jai Hind College]], [[Mumbai]] * ''[[Jai Hind (newspaper)|Jai Hind]]'', a Gujarati newspaper * ''[[JaiHind TV]]''.
