{{for|the village in Iran|Marid, Iran}}{{for|the IETF working group|MARID}}
'''''Marid''''' ({{lang-ar|مارد}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|mārid}}'') is an [[Arabic language|Arabic]] word meaning ''rebellious'', which is sometimes applied to supernatural beings.
==In Arabic sources ==
The word ''mārid'' is an [[Participle|active participle]] of the root ''m-r-d'' (مرد), whose primary meaning is ''recalcitrant, rebellious''. ''Lisān al-`arab'', the encyclopedic dictionary of classical Arabic compiled by [[Ibn Manzur]], reports only forms of this general meaning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alwaraq.net/Core/AlwaraqSrv/bookpage?book=89&fkey=2&page=5376&option=1 |author=Ibn Manzur |title=Lisan al-`arab (entry for m-r-d) |page=5376}}</ref> It is found as an attribute of evil spirits in the [[Quran|Qur'an]] (aṣ-Ṣāffāt, 37:7), which speaks of a "safeguard against every rebellious devil" (شَيْطَانٍ مَارِدٍ, ''shaitān mārid'').
The [[Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic|Wehr-Cowan dictionary]] of modern written Arabic also gives secondary meanings of ''demon'' and ''giant''.<ref>{{cite dictionary |first1=Hans |last1=Wehr |first2=J.M. |last2=Cowan |title=A Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic |edition=3rd |location=Ithaca, N.Y. |publisher=Spoken Language Services |page=903}}</ref> Lane's ''[[Arabic-English Lexicon]]'' cites a source where it "''is said to be applied to an evil jinnee of the most powerful class''",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tyndalearchive.com/tabs/lane/ |title=An Arabic-English Lexicon: Derived from the best and the most copious Eastern sources |first=Edward William |last=Lane |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408021742/http://www.tyndalearchive.com/tabs/lane/ |archivedate=2015-04-08 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> but this distinction is not universal. For example, in the standard MacNaghten edition of ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]'' one finds the words ''marid'' and ''[[ifrit]]'' used interchangeably (e.g., in ''The Story of the Fisherman'').<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/aliflailaorbook03unkngoog |title=Alif Laila |editor-first=Sir William Hay |editor-last=Mac Naghten |location=Calcutta |publisher=W. Thacker and Co |year=1839 |volume=1 |page=20 |language=Arabic}}</ref>
A mārid is explicitly mentioned in [[Sirat Sayf ibn Dhi-Yazan]]. Accordingly [[Sayf ibn Dhi-Yazan|Sayf]] demands from the marid to lead him to [[Solomon in Islam|Solomon]]s hoard. But following his nature, the demon does the exact oppisite of that he was commanded. Later he learned from [[Khidr]], he must command the opposite of that he desires him to do.<ref>Tobias Nünlist ''Dämonenglaube im Islam Walter'' de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG, 2015 {{ISBN|978-3-110-33168-4}} p. 100 (German) </ref>
==In modern fantasy genres == In Jonathan Stroud's ''[[Bartimaeus Sequence]]'' novel series, marids are the most powerful type of demons summoned by magicians.<ref>{{cite book |first=Jonathan |last=Stroud |title=The Amulet of Samarkand |series=The Bartimaeus Trilogy, Book&nbsp;1 |publisher=Disney-Hyperion |edition=Reprint |year=2004 |page=36}}</ref>
In the ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'' tabletop game, [[Marid (Dungeons & Dragons)|marids]] are genies from the Elemental Plane of Water.
